So the stage is set, the panellists have been decided on and we are only a couple of hours away from the Fiscal Treaty Debate on the Last Word on Today FM.

&#160;

<a href="http://blog.irishlife.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/stage2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1480" title="stage2" src="http://blog.irishlife.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/stage2.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="450" /></a>

&#160;

The debate will have a panel debating in favour of the Yes vote and a panel in favour of the No vote.  On the panel for the Yes vote is, Michael Martin, Fianna Fail Leader, Richard Bruton, Minister for Jobs, Enterprise and Innovation, and Nicola Byrne, Chief Executive 11890.  For the No vote we will be hearing from Mary Lou McDonald, Sinn Fein Deputy Leader, Nigel Farage, UKIP Leader and MEP and John Douglas, General Secretary of Mandate Trade Union.

The debate will be chaired by Matt Cooper and will be broadcast live on Today FM from 4.30pm.

If I had a euro for every time I have been asked “What does the eBusiness team do?” I might be on my way to Poznan now instead of sitting here writing this.  The general consensus seems to be that we chill out all day, updating our facebook pages, watching youtube on our iPads, and comparing the latests apps on our smartphones, but I can assure you, only some of that is correct!!

In February 2010, Shay Browne was appointed e Czar, and his first task was to assemble a team of young and hip people with their fingers on the pulse of internet and social media developments.  After finding that none of his top 100 candidates wanted to join the team, he settled for <a href="http://blog.irishlife.ie/author/stephen">Stephen Hayden</a> and myself as his first recruits.

Our first tasks were simple, modernise <a href="http://www.irishlife.ie/">www.irishlife.ie</a>, develop a pension calculator, develop a social media strategy for the company, build some iphone apps, get on Facebook, Twitter and basically be on top of what ever buzzword was cool at the time.  We quickly figured out that this was more than a two man job, and <a href="http://blog.irishlife.ie/author/colin">Colin O’Hara</a> was drafted in, <a href="http://blog.irishlife.ie/author/ger">Ger Coughlan</a> became the big boss man and later <a href="http://blog.irishlife.ie/author/george">George Fox</a> answered the call.
<p style="text-align: left;">Since then we have been constantly developing and improving the website, making it more user friendly and advice based.  We have built a range of online calculators, smartphone apps, started our own blog site, developed an online advertising strategy and are active on Facebook, Twitter and Google+.</p>

<blockquote>
<p style="text-align: left;">This app allows you to keep up to date with all your Irish Life Plans information while on the move.  Depending on your product type, you can check current values, payment history, investment history and fund performances.</p>
</blockquote>
Mobile is the latest buzzword doing the rounds, and keeping with that, we have developed our Online Services Smartphone App.  This app allows you to keep up to date with all your Irish Life Plans information while on the move.  Depending on your product type, you can check current values, payment history, investment history and fund performances.
