Irish Life today published their Interim Results for the first half of 2012, posting a profit (IFRS) of €96m – up six fold for the same period a year ago.  On an Embedded Value basis the Group recorded profits of €112m (2011: €5m loss) and the embedded value of the Group at the mid-year was €1.8 billion.

&#160;

[caption id="attachment_1669" align="aligncenter" width="523"]<img class=" wp-image-1669    " title="Total profit" src="http://blog.irishlife.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Total-profit.jpg" alt="" width="523" height="261" /> Irish Life Group Embedded Value profit/(loss) after tax[/caption]

&#160;

The company also reported an increase in life and investment sales of 6% compared to the same period a year ago and a rise of almost €2 billion in Funds Under Management at Irish Life Investment Managers.  The firm grew its market share in all key market segments and has a market share of 29% in the life and pensions market and over 1 million customers.  Its market share in fund management is 33%.  The company is the largest private payer of pensions in the country.

At a strategic level, the period was dominated by the separation of the businesses of Irish Life from those of permanent tsb and the acquisition of Irish Life’s businesses in June by the Minister for finance.

&#160;

[caption id="attachment_1665" align="aligncenter" width="523"]<img class=" wp-image-1665      " title="ILGroup" src="http://blog.irishlife.ie/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/ILGroup-1024x429.jpg" alt="Irish Life Group Structure" width="523" height="219" /> The Irish Life Group structure[/caption]

&#160;

Group Chief Executive Kevin Murphy acknowledged the support of the Minister and said the Group’s strategic priority was to ensure that the Minister’s investment could be fully recouped when the Group was ultimately returned to the private sector; “We’re very conscious of the support of the Minister and the taxpayer and we are determined to ensure that this can be repaid fully as soon as practicable.  We’re optimistic that this will be the case.”

Mr Murphy added that the economic environment remained very challenging and that retail sales of investment products in particular were hit by the lower levels of disposable income in the economy; “This is a very tough market and will remain so for a number of years.  But ultimately the economy will stabilise and recover and its clear that we are very well positioned to benefit from that when it occurs.  In the meantime our focus is firmly on managing costs, continuing to innovate in terms of product development and managing and improving our service levels for customers.”

Full details are available on the Group website <a href="http://www.irishlifegroup.ie">www.irishlifegroup.ie</a>

