With Father's Day around the corner, we surveyed 300 Irish Dads in a poll of "Most Inspiring Father". Barack Obama (1st) and Michael D. Higgins (2nd) topped the poll, with Keith Duffy and Ronan O'Gara following in 5th and 6th place respectively.

<iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/G9Gjtv9O5Zc" height="315" width="560" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0"></iframe>

&#160;

Our survey revealed some other insights into fathers in Ireland today including:

<strong>1. ‘Dad’</strong> is the most popular name for fathers (52%) with <b>‘Da’</b> (11%) and <b>‘Daddy’</b> (8%) the other most popular names.

&#160;

<strong>2. 27%</strong> of those surveyed claim ‘seeing their children grow and develop’ as the best part of being a father.

&#160;

<strong>3. 31%</strong> of those surveyed would consider a weekend away with their wife/partner as the ideal gift for Father’s Day, compared to <b>just 4%</b> who would prefer a golf day out with friends

&#160;

<strong>4.</strong> Playing in the park’ topped the poll at the favourite way to spend time with children (28%) with football being called out as the best game to play.

On a more serious note, children’s health ranks as the main concern for 1 in 3 fathers in Ireland today, ahead of being a good role model. Financial concerns are a concern for 2 in 5, a third cite providing for their children while a quarter refer to not being around for their children.

We've also made an infograph of our main research findings - have a look below.

